  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs when GVN
attempts to split a critical edge from a block containing an `indirectbr`
instruction. The `SplitKnownCriticalEdge` function has an assertion that
explicitly forbids splitting edges from `IndirectBrInst` because indirect
branches have special semantics - they can jump to any of their listed
destinations, and splitting edges would break this invariant.\n\n2. Analyzing
`opt`'s Log: The log shows that GVN is processing a foldable conditional branch
(`br i1 false`) in the `entry` block. Since the condition is `false`, the `ibr`
block becomes dead code. GVN then tries to handle this dead block by calling
`processFoldableCondBr`, which identifies `ibr` as the dead root and attempts
to split critical edges if it doesn't have a single predecessor.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis: In the reproducer, the `ibr` block contains an `indirectbr ptr
null, [label %exit, label %exit]` instruction. When `processFoldableCondBr`
determines that `ibr` is dead (since the branch condition is false), it checks
if `ibr` has a single predecessor. Since `ibr` has only one predecessor
(`entry`), the condition `!DeadRoot->getSinglePredecessor()` should be false,
and no splitting should occur. However, looking at the code more carefully, the
issue is that later in `addDeadBlock`, when processing the dominance frontier,
the code may still attempt to split critical edges from blocks that contain
`indirectbr` instructions. But actually, the immediate problem is in
`processFoldableCondBr` itself - it unconditionally calls `splitCriticalEdges`
when the dead root doesn't have a single predecessor, without checking if the
dead root's terminator is an `IndirectBrInst`.\n\nHowever, upon closer
inspection of the debugger output, we see that `DeadRoot` is the `ibr` block,
and the crash happens when trying to split the edge from `ibr` to `exit`. The
real issue is that in `addDeadBlock`, at line 3311, the code calls
`splitCriticalEdges(P, B)` where `P` is the `ibr` block (which contains an
`indirectbr`), and this eventually calls `SplitKnownCriticalEdge` which
asserts.\n\nBut wait, let me reconsider: In the reproducer, the `ibr` block has
only one predecessor (`entry`), so `DeadRoot->getSinglePredecessor()` should
return true, meaning line 3360 should not execute. However, the crash is
happening in `addDeadBlock`, not in the initial splitting. Looking at the stack
trace again: frame 6 is `processFoldableCondBr`, frame 5 is `addDeadBlock`, and
within `addDeadBlock`, at line 3311, it's calling `splitCriticalEdges(P, B)`
where `P` is a dead block that has an `indirectbr`.\n\nThe `ibr` block has
successors `[exit, exit]`, so it has multiple edges to `exit`. When
`addDeadBlock` processes the dominance frontier, it finds that `exit` is in the
dominance frontier (since it has both dead and live predecessors), and then
tries to split critical edges from dead predecessors (including `ibr`) to
`exit`. This is where the problem occurs - `ibr` contains an `indirectbr`, and
we cannot split edges from it.\n\nThe fix should be to check if a block's
terminator is an `IndirectBrInst` before attempting to split critical edges
from it. In both `processFoldableCondBr` (line 3359-3360) and in `addDeadBlock`
(line 3311), we need to avoid splitting edges from blocks with `indirectbr`
terminators.\n\nHowever, looking at the specific crash location and the fact
that the assertion is in `SplitKnownCriticalEdge`, the most direct fix is to
modify the `splitCriticalEdges` function or the callers to check for
`IndirectBrInst` before attempting to split.\n\nActually, examining the code in
`addDeadBlock` more carefully, the issue is at lines 3309-3312. Before calling
`splitCriticalEdges(P, B)`, we should check if `P`'s terminator is an
`IndirectBrInst`, and if so, skip the splitting.\n\nBut wait, there's another
consideration: in `processFoldableCondBr`, at line 3359-3360, we also need to
check for `IndirectBrInst` before splitting. However, in our specific case,
since `ibr` has a single predecessor, that code path shouldn't be taken. The
crash is happening in `addDeadBlock`.\n\nLooking at the stack trace again:
frame 14 is `addDeadBlock` calling `splitCriticalEdges` at line 3311. So the
fix should be in `addDeadBlock` to avoid splitting edges from blocks with
`IndirectBrInst` terminators.\n\nHowever, I notice that in the reproducer, the
`ibr` block is being marked as dead, and then in `addDeadBlock`, we're trying
